3
00:00:06.880 --> 00:00:09.760
digital biomarkers, and the future of cancer interception.

4
00:00:11.260 --> 00:00:13.880
My name is Peter Kuhn. I'm a university professor at the University of Southern

5
00:00:13.940 --> 00:00:15.280
California in Los Angeles.

6
00:00:16.700 --> 00:00:20.660
But before we start, I wanted to particularly welcome patients and advocates who

7
00:00:21.220 --> 00:00:24.599
might be with us in the audience. I'm glad that you guys are here.

8
00:00:25.600 --> 00:00:27.560
And

9
00:00:28.760 --> 00:00:32.701
as we go through Q&amp;A, the way we're setting up the session is

10
00:00:32.759 --> 00:00:36.560
that we will do 20 minutes per presentation with five minutes of

11
00:00:36.700 --> 00:00:37.020
Q&amp;A,

12
00:00:38.220 --> 00:00:41.060
so that we end up having about 15 minutes of

13
00:00:41.780 --> 00:00:44.060
combined Q&amp;A at the end

14
00:00:45.620 --> 00:00:45.940
of this.

15
00:00:47.940 --> 00:00:50.660
I'm super excited for the session in particular because we have,

16
00:00:51.640 --> 00:00:55.320
I think, Charissa, you're a clinical health psychologist, right?

17
00:00:56.660 --> 00:00:58.760
And Georgia is an information engineer by training.

18
00:00:59.660 --> 00:01:02.580
Jorge is an actual medical oncologist,

19
00:01:04.041 --> 00:01:07.200
so he's the physician in the room, and I'm a physicist by training.

20
00:01:07.860 --> 00:01:11.820
So hopefully we'll get a conversation actually going between all of us

21
00:01:11.840 --> 00:01:12.740
and through these

22
00:01:13.620 --> 00:01:15.880
different lenses, actually look at this topic.

23
00:01:19.840 --> 00:01:23.700
Jorge and I actually have taken a run at this now seven years ago

24
00:01:24.560 --> 00:01:28.540
at the AACR in 2019, and we did a bit of a playful

25
00:01:28.640 --> 00:01:31.000
construct of physician versus physicist.

26
00:01:31.740 --> 00:01:35.220
Because at the time, again, there was this idea of like, hey, the physics, we

27
00:01:35.320 --> 00:01:35.960
measure stuff,

28
00:01:36.760 --> 00:01:40.580
but the physician actually is there to actually advise the

29
00:01:40.620 --> 00:01:42.640
patient and develop a treatment plan.

30
00:01:43.720 --> 00:01:44.140
And

31
00:01:45.060 --> 00:01:47.760
then this construct of actually how do we actually work together, right?

32
00:01:47.780 --> 00:01:50.490
Because in the end, it's not measurement for the sake of measurement,

33
00:01:51.420 --> 00:01:53.840
but it really is about understanding the disease,

34
00:01:54.780 --> 00:01:58.560
and then really figuring out how can we actually improve outcomes through

35
00:01:59.000 --> 00:01:59.720
interventions.

36
00:02:01.220 --> 00:02:02.710
Still, I would argue still today,

37
00:02:03.580 --> 00:02:07.560
very much we look at cancer and cancer care as

38
00:02:07.660 --> 00:02:08.780
snapshots in time,

39
00:02:09.759 --> 00:02:12.720
maybe as far going as far as episodes is concerned.

40
00:02:14.440 --> 00:02:16.680
But that's really driven by how we observe it.

41
00:02:17.200 --> 00:02:20.020
It is not how the patient experiences it, because the patient, of course,

42
00:02:20.060 --> 00:02:20.840
experiences it

43
00:02:22.020 --> 00:02:23.560
as a continuum.

44
00:02:25.060 --> 00:02:28.620
So all of that framing, I think, is just there for us as

45
00:02:28.700 --> 00:02:32.470
a cancer research community to really think about

46
00:02:33.380 --> 00:02:36.720
what does that mean? How do we actually take that forward?

47
00:02:37.740 --> 00:02:41.620
And the not allowable one is to say, "Well, that's too complicated." Because again,

48
00:02:41.900 --> 00:02:43.740
what we really need to do is actually understand

49
00:02:44.660 --> 00:02:48.280
the human physiology and how it impacts

50
00:02:48.760 --> 00:02:52.310
the patient, and then how can we actually understand that

51
00:02:52.340 --> 00:02:56.290
evolving physiology, and then how can we measure that evolving physiology, and

52
00:02:56.320 --> 00:02:59.340
then how can we manipulate it for better outcomes.

53
00:03:00.700 --> 00:03:01.170
So with that,

54
00:03:03.440 --> 00:03:07.240
I'm actually going to make the introduction really short here to

55
00:03:08.240 --> 00:03:09.820
make room for Charissa,

56
00:03:10.640 --> 00:03:12.520
who is joining us from the University of Pittsburgh

57
00:03:13.540 --> 00:03:14.340
and UPMC.

58
00:03:15.200 --> 00:03:19.060
And this is really the most clinically grounded work, I think, in this space for us

59
00:03:19.140 --> 00:03:19.359
today.

60
00:03:20.640 --> 00:03:23.360
And with that, I'll just hand it over to you directly.

61
00:03:24.020 --> 00:03:27.940
As we go into Q&amp;A, please, everybody, walk up to the microphone, introduce

62
00:03:27.980 --> 00:03:30.460
yourself with name and affiliation, maybe really quick.

63
00:03:31.980 --> 00:03:35.720
But always use the microphone so that our online audience can hear your

64
00:03:35.780 --> 00:03:36.519
question as well.

65
00:03:40.100 --> 00:03:41.140
Great. Thank you, Peter.

66
00:03:41.940 --> 00:03:44.600
And thanks for the opportunity to share with you all some of the work that we're

67
00:03:44.660 --> 00:03:47.680
doing at the University of Pittsburgh and UPMC Hillman Cancer Center.

68
00:03:48.880 --> 00:03:52.230
So what I'd like to talk to you today about is an opportunity for all of us as

69
00:03:52.230 --> 00:03:53.920
cancer researchers and clinicians

70
00:03:54.900 --> 00:03:58.670
to better understand if a new experimental treatment is impacting patients'

71
00:03:58.760 --> 00:04:02.420
physical functioning, to identify which patients may be at risk for

72
00:04:02.440 --> 00:04:06.300
readmissions or falls after a long hospitalization, and to do this

73
00:04:06.360 --> 00:04:08.520
using data that many of your patients are already collecting.

74
00:04:08.600 --> 00:04:11.540
So you can tell by my title, I'm talking about consumer wearable devices.

75
00:04:13.500 --> 00:04:16.940
And these include things like Fitbits, Apple Watches, Oura Rings, things that

76
00:04:17.019 --> 00:04:19.060
anybody can buy at Amazon or Best Buy.

77
00:04:22.160 --> 00:04:23.000
Can you all hear me?

78
00:04:24.220 --> 00:04:28.170
Thank you. Can I just see a show of hands for who owns one of these devices

79
00:04:28.220 --> 00:04:30.680
or is wearing one right now?

80
00:04:31.720 --> 00:04:32.060
Thank you.

81
00:04:33.740 --> 00:04:37.570
So most of these measure objective behavior, including physical activity and

82
00:04:37.660 --> 00:04:41.460
sleep. So since they're measuring actual behavior, they really capture something

83
00:04:41.469 --> 00:04:45.240
different and less prone to recall and reporting biases than just

84
00:04:45.300 --> 00:04:48.120
asking a patient how much they exercise or how well they sleep.

85
00:04:49.370 --> 00:04:53.280
A lot of these also measure continuous physiology, things like heart rate, pulse

86
00:04:53.320 --> 00:04:55.120
oxygenation, skin temperature.

87
00:04:56.140 --> 00:04:59.860
Our most recent surveys from a couple of years ago suggest that nearly half of all

88
00:04:59.980 --> 00:05:03.360
US adults own and use a wearable device, and that ownership does tend to be

89
00:05:03.400 --> 00:05:07.000
concentrated among the younger, wealthier, more educated

90
00:05:07.140 --> 00:05:10.140
segments of the population, but that use is growing in all subgroups.

91
00:05:11.780 --> 00:05:14.280
And because users tend to wear these 24/7,

92
00:05:15.080 --> 00:05:18.880
we really are able to get a glimpse into the 99% of patients' lives when they are

93
00:05:18.920 --> 00:05:20.660
not in our clinical spaces in front of us.

94
00:05:21.420 --> 00:05:25.260
So we're able to capture their behavior and physiology between clinical

95
00:05:25.340 --> 00:05:28.860
visits as they're going about their usual daily

96
00:05:28.880 --> 00:05:31.900
routines in their homes and their communities when they're doing the things that

97
00:05:31.940 --> 00:05:35.860
matter most to them. And some reasons for why I think we should think

98
00:05:35.900 --> 00:05:39.580
about incorporating them into cancer care is that they're relatively inexpensive

99
00:05:39.600 --> 00:05:40.460
and easy to use.

100
00:05:41.540 --> 00:05:44.469
Important for remote monitoring is that the data can be accessed remotely,

101
00:05:44.540 --> 00:05:46.940
regardless of where the provider or the patient is.

102
00:05:47.620 --> 00:05:51.410
And in relatively real time, so that data can be actionable, we can pick up pretty

103
00:05:51.480 --> 00:05:53.200
quickly if something's going on with a patient.

104
00:05:54.720 --> 00:05:58.500
And because we're collecting such rich 24-hour data on patients, we can really get

105
00:05:58.540 --> 00:06:00.580
a sense of what's normal for that patient.

106
00:06:01.180 --> 00:06:04.520
What does their baseline look like, so that we can potentially pick up on subtle

107
00:06:04.620 --> 00:06:05.469
shifts in their health and

108
00:06:05.540 --> 00:06:09.480
functioning.In

109
00:06:09.500 --> 00:06:12.840
our lab, we've mostly used Fitbit Inspire devices, although I think the

110
00:06:13.200 --> 00:06:15.949
findings that I'll be presenting would generalize to data collected from other

111
00:06:15.960 --> 00:06:18.819
devices. And we've picked Fitbits for a few different reasons.

112
00:06:18.840 --> 00:06:21.260
First, they're pretty cheap at less than $100 per device.

113
00:06:22.500 --> 00:06:25.800
So this is important both for constrained grant budgets, but also for future

114
00:06:25.900 --> 00:06:26.500
scalability.

115
00:06:28.180 --> 00:06:31.260
Also important to us is that they're compatible with both iPhones and Android

116
00:06:31.270 --> 00:06:34.800
devices, unlike something like an Apple Watch or a Samsung watch.

117
00:06:35.300 --> 00:06:38.830
So this means that the patients can enroll in our studies or our monitoring

118
00:06:38.900 --> 00:06:42.080
protocols regardless of what kind of smartphone they have and use their own

119
00:06:42.140 --> 00:06:43.859
smartphone to sync the device and set it up.

120
00:06:46.100 --> 00:06:49.840
Fitbit Inspires have a 10-day battery life, which minimizes the burden on patients

121
00:06:49.860 --> 00:06:52.240
in terms of charging the device and remembering to put it back on.

122
00:06:53.820 --> 00:06:56.420
And the Fitbit Open API allows us to access data,

123
00:06:57.260 --> 00:07:01.120
granular intraday data that includes step count every minute, heart rate every few

124
00:07:01.220 --> 00:07:03.220
seconds, and sleep and physiology overnight.

125
00:07:03.790 --> 00:07:07.670
And there's evidence accumulating for sleep, for activity, and heart

126
00:07:07.720 --> 00:07:11.600
rate at least that these measures are relatively accurate compared to gold standard

127
00:07:11.620 --> 00:07:12.040
measures.

128
00:07:13.230 --> 00:07:16.900
So our team has collected Fitbit data from over 500 patients living with cancer

129
00:07:16.940 --> 00:07:20.720
over the past several years. We've developed a number of resources and procedures

130
00:07:20.760 --> 00:07:23.800
to try to make this as easy as possible for patients and for investigators.

131
00:07:23.860 --> 00:07:26.980
So if you're interested in doing this, please talk to me after the session.

132
00:07:28.580 --> 00:07:32.200
So the first question is: Is it feasible to collect Fitbit data during active

133
00:07:32.240 --> 00:07:34.930
cancer treatment? So when we're talking about active cancer treatment, we're

134
00:07:34.980 --> 00:07:37.920
obviously talking about older patients for the most part, patients that may not

135
00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:41.190
have a lot of digital health literacy or familiarity with wearable devices.

136
00:07:42.260 --> 00:07:45.360
And if they're going through chemotherapy or cancer treatment, they might not be

137
00:07:45.380 --> 00:07:47.000
feeling well. They might be feeling overwhelmed.

138
00:07:47.040 --> 00:07:50.060
Is this too much to ask for them to also collect this additional data stream?

139
00:07:51.500 --> 00:07:54.380
So this was a study led by a former medical student, Sean McLean.

140
00:07:55.200 --> 00:07:58.780
We enrolled 162 patients getting chemotherapy for any solid tumor.

141
00:08:00.340 --> 00:08:03.980
The patients in our sample were primarily gastrointestinal, pancreatic,

142
00:08:04.060 --> 00:08:07.200
breast, and other solid tumors. And they were asked to wear a Fitbit device that we

143
00:08:07.260 --> 00:08:10.900
provided for 90 days, and we encouraged them to keep it at the end of the study.

144
00:08:12.720 --> 00:08:16.710
Patients on average were 60 years old, but we had people as old as 92 enroll in

145
00:08:16.720 --> 00:08:20.330
our study, 62% female, 83% white, and you can see that over

146
00:08:20.420 --> 00:08:23.700
two-thirds had stage four cancer. So at least some patients were relatively sick.

147
00:08:25.320 --> 00:08:29.180
So in our lab, we use the availability of heart rate data to indicate wear

148
00:08:29.220 --> 00:08:31.300
time, and we set a minimum threshold of eight hours.

149
00:08:31.340 --> 00:08:35.081
We want patients wearing the device for at least a third of the day and around half

150
00:08:35.120 --> 00:08:38.380
of their waking hours if we're going to include that step count in our assessment

151
00:08:38.420 --> 00:08:39.560
of how active they were that day.

152
00:08:40.520 --> 00:08:44.380
And we found that on average, patients met that threshold on 70% of study

153
00:08:44.420 --> 00:08:47.360
days over the 90-day study, which we found encouraging.

154
00:08:47.920 --> 00:08:50.660
It suggests that we're getting a pretty good sense of how active people are

155
00:08:50.700 --> 00:08:54.380
being out in the real world in between their clinical visits and their

156
00:08:54.400 --> 00:08:58.280
chemotherapy infusions. Also really encouraging and important to us was that we

157
00:08:58.320 --> 00:09:00.240
didn't see this rate decline over time.

158
00:09:00.420 --> 00:09:03.800
So we didn't see that people eventually got fed up with the Fitbit and stopped

159
00:09:03.840 --> 00:09:06.290
wearing it, that they stopped charging it or remembering to put it on.

160
00:09:06.980 --> 00:09:09.960
Rates were pretty consistent throughout the 90 days, suggesting that we may be able

161
00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:12.100
to extend this monitoring period even further.

162
00:09:14.740 --> 00:09:18.020
We also looked at sociodemographic and clinical factors related to Fitbit

163
00:09:18.060 --> 00:09:18.640
adherence.

164
00:09:19.600 --> 00:09:22.760
We found an effect of age, but in the opposite direction that we hypothesized.

165
00:09:22.780 --> 00:09:25.460
We actually found that our older patients were better at collecting Fitbit data

166
00:09:25.500 --> 00:09:26.460
than our younger patients.

167
00:09:27.560 --> 00:09:31.290
No gender difference. We found a pretty striking race difference with our non-white

168
00:09:31.340 --> 00:09:32.020
participants.

169
00:09:32.920 --> 00:09:36.360
Again, only 17% of our sample, but they had much lower rates of Fitbit adherence,

170
00:09:36.480 --> 00:09:39.240
so we're still digging into trying to understand the reasons for that and how we

171
00:09:39.260 --> 00:09:40.460
can mitigate that disparity.

172
00:09:41.500 --> 00:09:43.540
No difference by education or rurality.

173
00:09:44.320 --> 00:09:47.089
We found that patients that came into the study with any level of cognitive

174
00:09:47.140 --> 00:09:50.540
impairment by self-report also struggled a little bit with the Fitbit data

175
00:09:50.600 --> 00:09:51.040
collection.

176
00:09:51.950 --> 00:09:55.680
No difference by depression or cancer stage, again, by study day or

177
00:09:55.760 --> 00:09:56.580
weekend or weekday.

178
00:09:57.400 --> 00:10:00.700
We did find that patients were better at collecting Fitbit data in the days right

179
00:10:00.760 --> 00:10:04.260
after their chemotherapy infusions, which may partly be an artifact of the fact

180
00:10:04.270 --> 00:10:07.600
that we often showed up in the infusion room to help them sync their Fitbit, get

181
00:10:07.640 --> 00:10:10.630
re-logged in, but also may indicate that

182
00:10:10.660 --> 00:10:14.240
those days right after their infusion when they were experiencing the most side

183
00:10:14.280 --> 00:10:16.869
effects, maybe their health and wellbeing was more top of mind, and they were

184
00:10:16.880 --> 00:10:20.860
remembering to keep the Fitbit charged and on their body.

185
00:10:21.620 --> 00:10:23.520
So this is my answer to can we do this?

186
00:10:23.600 --> 00:10:26.580
Can we collect Fitbit data during active cancer treatment?

187
00:10:26.620 --> 00:10:28.219
So next I'm going to turn to should we do this?

188
00:10:28.260 --> 00:10:31.960
Is there any clinical value in these Fitbit data in terms of cancer outcomes?

189
00:10:33.540 --> 00:10:36.760
So the first study we did in this space was looking at hospital readmissions.

190
00:10:37.420 --> 00:10:41.240
So we enrolled 54 patients undergoing surgical treatment for metastatic peritoneal

191
00:10:41.280 --> 00:10:44.900
cancer. So if any of you are surgeons or have had surgery or helped somebody

192
00:10:44.920 --> 00:10:48.350
through surgery, you know that patients are always told to get up and get moving as

193
00:10:48.380 --> 00:10:51.460
soon as possible after you've had surgery, that that will speed their recovery and

194
00:10:51.500 --> 00:10:54.120
healing. But this is rarely quantified systematically.

195
00:10:54.620 --> 00:10:57.600
So that's what we set out to do. We gave patients a Fitbit to wear from the time

196
00:10:57.640 --> 00:11:01.580
that they left the ICU and were ambulatory until their hospital discharge, which

197
00:11:01.600 --> 00:11:03.260
was around 12 days for most patients.

198
00:11:04.960 --> 00:11:08.260
These patients were getting cytoreductive surgery with hypothermic intraperitoneal

199
00:11:08.300 --> 00:11:11.260
chemotherapy, which is a pretty grueling procedure with a high complication and

200
00:11:11.300 --> 00:11:15.240
readmission rate. And consistent with that, we found that 39% of our patients

201
00:11:15.320 --> 00:11:17.020
were readmitted within 60 days.

202
00:11:18.720 --> 00:11:21.700
And when we looked at how active they had been during that inpatient recovery, we

203
00:11:21.740 --> 00:11:24.690
saw that the patients that left the hospital after their surgery and did not come

204
00:11:24.760 --> 00:11:28.360
back were more active. They were taking around 1,250 steps per

205
00:11:28.420 --> 00:11:31.880
day, which is significant right after a major abdominal surgery.

206
00:11:31.930 --> 00:11:35.800
Suggests some intentional efforts to get up and walk around the hallways.

207
00:11:36.020 --> 00:11:39.100
The patients that were readmitted were more around 500 steps a

208
00:11:39.180 --> 00:11:42.840
day. And this effect persisted even after we adjusted for things that might be

209
00:11:42.940 --> 00:11:46.540
related to both activity and readmission, so age, comorbidity,

210
00:11:46.680 --> 00:11:50.480
BMI, and length of stay. So I'm not suggesting that this is causal.

211
00:11:50.540 --> 00:11:53.110
There's a lot of other factors that could be at play here, but it does suggest that

212
00:11:53.140 --> 00:11:57.110
these pretty easy-to-collect Fitbit data may help us figure out

213
00:11:57.160 --> 00:12:01.050
who after these surgeries might benefit from additional support and

214
00:12:01.100 --> 00:12:05.032
monitoring.So

215
00:12:05.112 --> 00:12:07.632
step count is kind of the first thing you think about when you think of Fitbit

216
00:12:07.652 --> 00:12:11.571
devices. But because we're collecting continuous data over 24 hours, there's a

217
00:12:11.592 --> 00:12:15.022
lot of other information that we can extract from that data.

218
00:12:15.652 --> 00:12:19.492
So a former postdoc, Dr. Julio Vega, developed an open source pipeline for data

219
00:12:19.532 --> 00:12:21.612
cleaning and processing called Rapids.

220
00:12:21.912 --> 00:12:24.812
If you work in this space, I encourage you to check it out at rapids.science.

221
00:12:25.272 --> 00:12:27.302
So we've been using this to compute additional features.

222
00:12:27.332 --> 00:12:28.532
We're always adding to the pipeline.

223
00:12:28.552 --> 00:12:28.652
We

224
00:12:29.532 --> 00:12:32.912
like other contributors to add things as well.

225
00:12:33.152 --> 00:12:35.772
So some things that we've been adding and focused on the last couple of years that

226
00:12:35.792 --> 00:12:39.252
we think are nice complements to step count, which really reflects the amount of

227
00:12:39.292 --> 00:12:40.092
walking activity,

228
00:12:41.112 --> 00:12:44.932
is peak gait cadence, which is maximum steps per minute, which really reflects the

229
00:12:44.952 --> 00:12:46.832
intensity of walking at peak effort,

230
00:12:48.052 --> 00:12:51.792
and activity fragmentation, which is the probability of transitioning from an

231
00:12:51.872 --> 00:12:54.972
active to a sedentary state. So if somebody is walking, do they need to stop and

232
00:12:55.012 --> 00:12:57.772
rest? And this reflects stamina while walking.

233
00:12:58.372 --> 00:13:02.212
So we picked these because, in the research-grade accelerometry literature, there's

234
00:13:02.232 --> 00:13:05.852
some evidence that these metrics predict frailty,

235
00:13:06.012 --> 00:13:08.951
falls, and mortality in community-dwelling older adults.

236
00:13:09.112 --> 00:13:11.792
They've not really been looked at in the context of cancer, and these haven't been

237
00:13:11.832 --> 00:13:14.192
extracted from consumer wearable device data before.

238
00:13:15.332 --> 00:13:17.872
So we were interested in whether we could do that with Fitbit data and whether

239
00:13:17.912 --> 00:13:20.792
those would be predictive of any important clinical cancer outcomes.

240
00:13:22.812 --> 00:13:26.452
So we first did a study with post-treatment cancer survivors, and here we were

241
00:13:26.492 --> 00:13:29.992
focused on survivors aged 65 and up who may be at elevated risk for things like

242
00:13:30.032 --> 00:13:33.872
falls and functional decline. We enrolled 40 survivors of any

243
00:13:33.912 --> 00:13:35.412
cancer within five years of treatment.

244
00:13:36.452 --> 00:13:40.412
We had them come into our lab and do some objective performance-based

245
00:13:40.472 --> 00:13:43.222
physical functioning tests, including the Short Physical Performance Battery.

246
00:13:43.692 --> 00:13:46.852
We also had them fill out questionnaires to assess their self-reported physical

247
00:13:46.872 --> 00:13:49.882
functioning. And then we had them wear a Fitbit for a month and computed these

248
00:13:49.912 --> 00:13:50.472
variables.

249
00:13:51.452 --> 00:13:54.752
And in terms of correlations, we found that step count was

250
00:13:55.212 --> 00:13:57.992
correlated with patient-reported physical functioning and the Short Physical

251
00:13:58.052 --> 00:13:59.111
Performance Battery score.

252
00:14:00.012 --> 00:14:03.002
Correlations were maybe even a little stronger for gait cadence and activity

253
00:14:03.092 --> 00:14:06.952
fragmentation. When we adjusted for age and comorbidities, only

254
00:14:06.972 --> 00:14:10.202
peak gait cadence was related to PROMIS physical functioning,

255
00:14:10.912 --> 00:14:14.052
although all features remained associated with that objective performance-based

256
00:14:14.112 --> 00:14:14.812
physical functioning.

257
00:14:17.072 --> 00:14:20.532
We also found that about a third of participants reported a fall or a near fall

258
00:14:20.552 --> 00:14:24.232
during the one-month study. So we were interested in whether these variables were

259
00:14:24.312 --> 00:14:25.572
useful for predicting falls.

260
00:14:26.892 --> 00:14:30.212
So in some regression analyses, again, adjusting for age and comorbidities, we

261
00:14:30.272 --> 00:14:34.261
found that faster peak gait cadence alone was associated with significantly reduced

262
00:14:34.332 --> 00:14:35.672
fall risk during that one month.

263
00:14:36.612 --> 00:14:40.312
We did some ROC curve analyses that suggested that peak gait cadence was able to

264
00:14:40.332 --> 00:14:44.192
differentiate those survivors at risk for falls versus those not, and that the

265
00:14:44.232 --> 00:14:47.752
optimal threshold for cutoff was around 100 steps per minute, which is like a brisk

266
00:14:47.812 --> 00:14:48.112
walk.

267
00:14:51.692 --> 00:14:54.062
Next, we turn to see whether this could predict survival.

268
00:14:54.201 --> 00:14:58.032
So this is an extension of that earlier sample of patients

269
00:14:58.072 --> 00:14:59.912
getting chemotherapy for any solid tumors.

270
00:14:59.972 --> 00:15:03.132
We had 213 patients enroll and wear the Fitbit for 90 days.

271
00:15:04.452 --> 00:15:08.192
We followed patients for a median of two and a half years, and we found that 42% of

272
00:15:08.232 --> 00:15:12.052
patients died during that time. In univariate analyses,

273
00:15:12.132 --> 00:15:14.232
we found that step count did predict survival.

274
00:15:14.732 --> 00:15:16.812
So did peak gait cadence and activity fragmentation.

275
00:15:16.832 --> 00:15:20.572
But when we adjusted for age and cancer stage and type, only the latter two

276
00:15:20.592 --> 00:15:23.412
variables, only peak gait cadence and activity fragmentation remained

277
00:15:23.432 --> 00:15:24.852
significant.

278
00:15:25.772 --> 00:15:28.152
So you can see our Kaplan-Meier curves here.

279
00:15:28.232 --> 00:15:29.612
So on the

280
00:15:30.832 --> 00:15:34.812
top panel, you can see gait cadence, the participants walking whose peak

281
00:15:34.912 --> 00:15:36.072
gait cadence was 100 or more

282
00:15:37.432 --> 00:15:40.432
in the yellow line on top had better survival, and in the bottom, you can see that

283
00:15:40.472 --> 00:15:44.052
the patients that had more fragmented activity in the yellow had

284
00:15:45.372 --> 00:15:47.052
greater mortality over the follow-up.

285
00:15:48.072 --> 00:15:51.782
And so as I said, these associations persisted when we adjusted for age, cancer

286
00:15:51.892 --> 00:15:55.832
stage, cancer type. Also importantly, they persisted when we adjusted

287
00:15:55.852 --> 00:15:59.512
for clinician-rated ECOG performance status, when we adjusted for

288
00:15:59.532 --> 00:16:00.882
patient-reported physical functioning.

289
00:16:01.652 --> 00:16:04.112
And I didn't do this in the paper, but I thought of it later and also adjusted for

290
00:16:04.212 --> 00:16:07.712
step count, and these associations remained when we adjusted for step count.

291
00:16:08.212 --> 00:16:11.892
So suggesting that these gait cadence and activity fragmentation measures might be

292
00:16:11.932 --> 00:16:15.472
capturing something independent of what clinicians can perceive, what patients can

293
00:16:15.512 --> 00:16:18.472
perceive, and something different than just a generic step count.

294
00:16:22.072 --> 00:16:24.852
Alongside this quantitative work, we've been doing some qualitative studies with

295
00:16:24.872 --> 00:16:28.181
both clinicians and patients. Talk about the work with clinicians today.

296
00:16:29.092 --> 00:16:32.652
So we interviewed 13 oncology clinicians who did some questionnaires.

297
00:16:32.692 --> 00:16:35.812
We also interviewed them to try to understand their preferences around how we may

298
00:16:35.872 --> 00:16:39.702
integrate some of this wearable device data into clinical care, clinical

299
00:16:39.752 --> 00:16:42.732
decision-making, and into patient-provider communication.

300
00:16:44.812 --> 00:16:48.732
During the interviews, we had a few clinical vignettes where we

301
00:16:48.792 --> 00:16:52.692
had some clinical information, and then alongside that showed some data

302
00:16:52.732 --> 00:16:55.552
from the past participants in our studies, some wearable device data, to see

303
00:16:55.572 --> 00:16:59.322
whether that had any influence on their clinical decisions and recommendations and

304
00:16:59.332 --> 00:17:00.772
their confidence in those decisions.

305
00:17:02.612 --> 00:17:06.072
Overall, the clinicians did report that the data from wearable devices improved

306
00:17:06.083 --> 00:17:08.732
their confidence and their clinical understanding and decisions.

307
00:17:10.052 --> 00:17:11.652
Just have a couple illustrative quotes here.

308
00:17:12.123 --> 00:17:15.312
"It'd be nice if someone's calling me with questions, I can just pull up this data

309
00:17:15.333 --> 00:17:17.192
and see what's really going on between visits."

310
00:17:18.572 --> 00:17:21.373
"Sometimes I feel like patients don't want to be dose reduced and they'll lie.

311
00:17:21.432 --> 00:17:24.702
I try to get their family to rat them out, like, 'Are they really grocery shopping

312
00:17:24.702 --> 00:17:27.532
and cutting the lawn?' And they say, 'No, they're sitting on the couch all day.'"

313
00:17:27.613 --> 00:17:31.132
So what we heard a lot from clinicians was that this wearable device data was a

314
00:17:31.172 --> 00:17:34.992
nice complementary piece of information that could corroborate or

315
00:17:35.032 --> 00:17:38.712
help to resolve discrepancies in reports, kind of what they were seeing, what the

316
00:17:38.752 --> 00:17:40.652
patient was telling them, what the family was telling them.

317
00:17:41.832 --> 00:17:45.072
And so while it didn't necessarily change their recommendation or decisions, it

318
00:17:45.112 --> 00:17:47.892
just gave them greater confidence in those decisions and understanding.

319
00:17:50.152 --> 00:17:51.472
So some lessons learned so far.

320
00:17:52.912 --> 00:17:56.532
Consumer wearable device data can be reliably collected from even older advanced

321
00:17:56.572 --> 00:17:59.822
cancer patients and for several months and perhaps longer during active treatment.

322
00:18:01.432 --> 00:18:04.792
Fitbit metrics, at least in our preliminary, pretty small samples,

323
00:18:05.632 --> 00:18:09.212
but they suggest that these Fitbit metrics are related to readmission risk after

324
00:18:09.292 --> 00:18:12.602
cancer surgery, physical functioning and fall risk after cancer treatment, and

325
00:18:12.692 --> 00:18:16.242
survival after chemotherapy.And that peak gait cadence and activity

326
00:18:16.262 --> 00:18:19.672
fragmentation from these devices may be more prognostic than step count in the

327
00:18:19.702 --> 00:18:23.041
context of cancer and might also capture information about real-world

328
00:18:23.102 --> 00:18:25.982
functioning, independent of what clinicians and patients perceive.

329
00:18:27.282 --> 00:18:28.322
And oncology clinicians,

330
00:18:29.162 --> 00:18:32.342
at least the ones we talked to, believe that wearable device data could improve

331
00:18:32.382 --> 00:18:33.982
confidence in clinical decisions.

332
00:18:37.942 --> 00:18:41.021
In some ongoing work, we're trying to figure out how can we best share these data

333
00:18:41.062 --> 00:18:44.662
with oncology patients and clinicians. Do they want alerts?

334
00:18:44.812 --> 00:18:47.682
Do they want visualizations of these data that they can sift through and find

335
00:18:47.722 --> 00:18:51.092
patterns on their own? Do they want to receive things via email, in-app

336
00:18:51.142 --> 00:18:54.802
notifications? So we have a single-arm trial ongoing right now with

337
00:18:54.842 --> 00:18:58.702
39 patients. Our cancer center is currently transitioning to Epic this year,

338
00:18:58.782 --> 00:19:02.632
so we had some limitations in being able to integrate anything into the medical

339
00:19:02.682 --> 00:19:03.902
record, not this year.

340
00:19:05.002 --> 00:19:08.482
So what we're doing in this trial is we're using patient

341
00:19:08.522 --> 00:19:12.262
smartphones to have them complete a daily patient-reported outcome measure

342
00:19:12.282 --> 00:19:14.602
assessing seven common symptoms during chemotherapy.

343
00:19:15.282 --> 00:19:18.902
If symptoms are mild, they get some self-management advice that are based on

344
00:19:18.941 --> 00:19:20.862
clinical guidelines that pop up within the app.

345
00:19:21.482 --> 00:19:24.242
If they endorse anything moderate to severe, they get an alert that they should

346
00:19:24.262 --> 00:19:27.932
consider contacting their clinician to discuss these symptoms, especially if they

347
00:19:27.942 --> 00:19:28.762
persist or worsen.

348
00:19:30.032 --> 00:19:31.402
They're also wearing a Fitbit device.

349
00:19:31.442 --> 00:19:34.262
We have an automated nightly script that's running each night to check their Fitbit

350
00:19:34.282 --> 00:19:38.102
data for low pulse ox, elevated skin temperature,

351
00:19:38.902 --> 00:19:42.282
a heart rate that's 10% higher than that patient's historic average,

352
00:19:42.842 --> 00:19:45.822
or a step count or gait cadence that's significantly lower than their historic

353
00:19:45.882 --> 00:19:49.362
average. And if any of these are detected, again, they get an alert saying, "You

354
00:19:49.382 --> 00:19:52.002
might want to consider discussing this with your clinician, especially if you're

355
00:19:52.062 --> 00:19:53.402
also experiencing symptoms."

356
00:19:56.422 --> 00:19:59.372
In addition, we have a weekly script that's automatically generating and emailing

357
00:19:59.442 --> 00:20:03.382
patients a report that's visualizing this data, which we encourage them to share

358
00:20:03.462 --> 00:20:06.622
with their family members, their caregivers, as well as their clinical care team.

359
00:20:07.282 --> 00:20:09.142
And here's just some screenshots from those reports.

360
00:20:09.172 --> 00:20:12.542
So we have a heat map showing the different symptoms that are reported daily,

361
00:20:14.262 --> 00:20:17.942
decreased appetite, fatigue, the kind of common symptoms that patients

362
00:20:18.002 --> 00:20:21.542
report. And then you can see some graphs of their Fitbit data, and the red dots are

363
00:20:21.582 --> 00:20:24.682
any time an alert was triggered, an email sent to them, or an alert sent to the

364
00:20:24.702 --> 00:20:26.572
patient suggesting they talk to their clinician.

365
00:20:28.782 --> 00:20:32.582
We're also doing similar remote monitoring studies in the context of cystectomy for

366
00:20:32.602 --> 00:20:35.702
bladder cancer, as well as for patients getting immune checkpoint inhibitors for

367
00:20:35.722 --> 00:20:36.162
melanoma.

368
00:20:38.562 --> 00:20:41.922
Clinicians are really busy. They may or may not want to sift through all these

369
00:20:41.982 --> 00:20:45.162
lovely graphs that we're generating for them, so we're also exploring the role of

370
00:20:45.202 --> 00:20:49.062
AI in summarizing these data for clinicians to see whether LLMs may be

371
00:20:49.122 --> 00:20:53.042
useful in generating narrative summaries that may be easier for clinicians to

372
00:20:53.082 --> 00:20:54.342
integrate into their workflows.

373
00:20:55.412 --> 00:20:58.662
And we're developing patient-facing tools to help them identify patterns in their

374
00:20:58.702 --> 00:21:02.642
wearable device data to guide behavioral change or to prepare

375
00:21:02.682 --> 00:21:04.702
for their clinical visits and their conversations with their

376
00:21:04.742 --> 00:21:08.722
clinicians. So I'm really excited about this field.

377
00:21:09.322 --> 00:21:12.402
I'd be happy to collaborate with anybody here, and I'm excited to hear from my

378
00:21:12.442 --> 00:21:15.382
fellow panelists about where we can consider taking this field more broadly.

379
00:21:17.022 --> 00:21:19.831
So I'd like to acknowledge our-- We have a great interdisciplinary team at the

380
00:21:19.882 --> 00:21:21.802
Mobile Sensing and Health Institute at Pitt.

381
00:21:22.962 --> 00:21:24.762
You can check out our projects on our website.

382
00:21:25.952 --> 00:21:29.302
The patients and clinicians who participated in this work, most of our funding has

383
00:21:29.322 --> 00:21:31.222
been from NCI, and thank you all for listening.

384
00:21:38.542 --> 00:21:42.202
Any questions, please come up to the microphone.

385
00:21:43.742 --> 00:21:45.862
Carissa, maybe one quick question.

386
00:21:45.902 --> 00:21:48.812
When you show the data on predicting falls,

387
00:21:51.182 --> 00:21:55.122
have you tried to see how early you could predict

388
00:21:55.132 --> 00:21:57.402
that reliably, right? It's one thing to-

389
00:21:57.502 --> 00:21:57.602
Yeah

390
00:21:57.611 --> 00:21:59.302
... retroactively say-

391
00:21:59.312 --> 00:21:59.322
Right

392
00:21:59.331 --> 00:22:01.331
... we can separate those two, but-

393
00:22:01.862 --> 00:22:02.012
Yeah

394
00:22:02.012 --> 00:22:02.732
... how do you think about that?

395
00:22:03.042 --> 00:22:04.152
Absolutely. No, we have not

396
00:22:05.002 --> 00:22:07.062
attempted that yet. I think that's really critically important.

397
00:22:07.102 --> 00:22:10.122
What kind of early warning time window does that give us?

398
00:22:10.342 --> 00:22:12.902
I think that is really the important question, because a lot of what I'm presenting

399
00:22:12.962 --> 00:22:16.252
is retrospective analyses where we're looking at data that's been collected and

400
00:22:16.282 --> 00:22:20.002
linking it to clinical outcomes. But whether when actually deployed, we're able

401
00:22:20.142 --> 00:22:24.082
to predict things sooner than we otherwise would have and act

402
00:22:24.242 --> 00:22:26.042
sooner is still an open question.

403
00:22:27.702 --> 00:22:30.982
Hi there. I'm Chi-Chun Hong from Roswell Park Comprehensive Cancer

404
00:22:31.062 --> 00:22:34.702
Center. So we're trying to get into this field as well, and we're

405
00:22:34.711 --> 00:22:38.582
trying to, right now, put together a study of

406
00:22:39.002 --> 00:22:42.392
1,000 metastatic breast cancer patients across five different states,

407
00:22:43.022 --> 00:22:44.862
and we're trying to use some of these sensors.

408
00:22:44.902 --> 00:22:48.782
And I'm just wondering if there was a process for you to get to

409
00:22:48.862 --> 00:22:52.652
Fitbit as opposed to some of the other devices out

410
00:22:52.702 --> 00:22:53.122
there.

411
00:22:54.302 --> 00:22:58.062
Mm-hmm. Yeah. Yes, we tried at least a dozen wearable devices when we were starting

412
00:22:58.182 --> 00:23:01.342
out. Again, I showed some of the rationale for selecting Fitbit.

413
00:23:01.382 --> 00:23:04.742
We really did want something that was platform agnostic that could work

414
00:23:04.782 --> 00:23:05.482
across

415
00:23:06.582 --> 00:23:10.042
both Android and iPhones. A lot of our older patients do have Android phones,

416
00:23:11.342 --> 00:23:14.062
and where there was an open API that we could work with.

417
00:23:14.142 --> 00:23:18.002
And we landed on Fitbits back in 2016, 2017, and have just

418
00:23:18.042 --> 00:23:20.662
stuck with it because that's the infrastructure that we've been developing.

419
00:23:21.562 --> 00:23:23.642
And I think there's a lot of advantages and disadvantages.

420
00:23:23.722 --> 00:23:26.472
I think now that they've been acquired by Google, there's some additional hiccups

421
00:23:26.482 --> 00:23:30.302
that we're working through. But I do think that patients generally find them really

422
00:23:30.322 --> 00:23:33.942
comfortable and easy to use. A lot of patients have Fitbits already, and if so,

423
00:23:33.982 --> 00:23:36.042
we're just able to access data from their account.

424
00:23:36.462 --> 00:23:40.362
Right. Okay. We ended up going with Garmin, and I'm like having to rethink

425
00:23:40.402 --> 00:23:41.882
this. Can I ask one more question?

426
00:23:41.942 --> 00:23:42.322
Of course.

427
00:23:42.702 --> 00:23:46.462
So we ran into some issues where some of the patients came

428
00:23:46.562 --> 00:23:49.942
back and they said, "I wear Apple Watch. This is what I'm going to wear.

429
00:23:50.622 --> 00:23:51.622
I don't want to wear a Garmin."

430
00:23:51.882 --> 00:23:51.982
Yeah.

431
00:23:52.282 --> 00:23:54.582
Have you dealt with trying to

432
00:23:56.062 --> 00:23:59.602
bring together these different kinds of data and letting patients wear what they

433
00:23:59.662 --> 00:24:00.222
want to wear?

434
00:24:00.502 --> 00:24:01.842
Yeah, I would love to get to that point.

435
00:24:01.942 --> 00:24:05.422
I think it's complicated if you're trying to work directly with the data.

436
00:24:05.482 --> 00:24:09.442
There are a number of companies out there that are data aggregators, where you can

437
00:24:10.842 --> 00:24:13.812
contribute whatever data from whatever device and pull that in.

438
00:24:13.812 --> 00:24:16.842
And then I think they have ways of harmonizing the data so you can consider step

439
00:24:16.922 --> 00:24:19.362
count from whatever device the patient is already owning and using.

440
00:24:19.382 --> 00:24:22.042
And that might be a way to go. They're kind of expensive, those companies, but-

441
00:24:22.182 --> 00:24:22.372
Okay

442
00:24:22.382 --> 00:24:25.942
... I think, yeah, in terms of pragmatically integrating these

443
00:24:25.982 --> 00:24:29.702
into clinical workflow, I think letting people use what they have is going to

444
00:24:29.962 --> 00:24:31.161
be really important for engagement.

445
00:24:31.502 --> 00:24:32.302
Okay. Thank you.

446
00:24:34.592 --> 00:24:35.932
Karissa, one more question on the-

447
00:24:36.192 --> 00:24:36.292
Yeah

448
00:24:36.432 --> 00:24:39.372
... on the data. So you're returning data to the patient.

449
00:24:39.552 --> 00:24:43.212
What you showed was a fairly pragmatic return of data.

450
00:24:43.272 --> 00:24:43.472
Mm-hmm.

451
00:24:44.052 --> 00:24:47.992
Somewhere along the way, you're going to return interpreted data

452
00:24:48.692 --> 00:24:52.252
or data interpretation. Where is that balance on the

453
00:24:52.332 --> 00:24:53.592
IRB in terms of-

454
00:24:53.672 --> 00:24:53.972
Mm-hmm

455
00:24:54.551 --> 00:24:58.042
... returning results on a research approach?

456
00:24:58.072 --> 00:24:59.712
How does that work?

457
00:25:00.012 --> 00:25:00.362
Yeah.

458
00:25:00.372 --> 00:25:03.882
What can we learn from your experience of how to actually design this?

459
00:25:04.172 --> 00:25:08.012
Yeah. I'm definitely not an expert in this space, and we have really tried to toe

460
00:25:08.092 --> 00:25:11.922
the line of regulatory, like not crossing the line into being a

461
00:25:11.952 --> 00:25:14.172
medical device. We're not trying to diagnose anything.

462
00:25:15.352 --> 00:25:18.592
And yeah, the data that we're returning, the IRB has determined is not

463
00:25:18.892 --> 00:25:20.732
diagnostic or anything too interpretive.

464
00:25:20.832 --> 00:25:21.172
I think,

465
00:25:22.232 --> 00:25:23.732
it's really a changing landscape.

466
00:25:23.832 --> 00:25:24.192
I think,

467
00:25:25.552 --> 00:25:26.242
since we're not

468
00:25:27.952 --> 00:25:31.912
providing data in real time, that since we're not using it to affect insulin

469
00:25:31.932 --> 00:25:34.492
dose or anything like that, it's been okay for IRB.

470
00:25:34.572 --> 00:25:37.192
But yeah, I'm definitely not the best person to ask about this.

471
00:25:37.252 --> 00:25:40.432
I think it is a question that we all need to put our heads together to figure out

472
00:25:40.672 --> 00:25:44.652
how to get data to patients that is actionable and useful for them, but

473
00:25:44.692 --> 00:25:48.612
that isn't going to introduce more risks that we don't quite understand.

474
00:25:49.952 --> 00:25:50.052
Yeah.

475
00:25:50.452 --> 00:25:54.132
Hi. Have you attempted any temporal mapping of

476
00:25:54.212 --> 00:25:57.352
activity trends with when they had

477
00:25:57.652 --> 00:26:00.572
treatment and what type of treatment perhaps too?

478
00:26:00.792 --> 00:26:02.032
Are there any insights from that?

479
00:26:02.312 --> 00:26:03.532
Yeah. That's a great question.

