as they can, but then it's their own choice what they want to do.

993
00:55:31.436 --> 00:55:35.216
Hi, thank you. That was actually kind of a good segue into my question about

994
00:55:35.276 --> 00:55:39.156
longitudinal monitoring. So when it comes to the actual data

995
00:55:39.416 --> 00:55:43.336
and dropouts, say, the patient takes off their wearable device for a

996
00:55:43.376 --> 00:55:44.296
certain amount of time,

997
00:55:45.096 --> 00:55:48.736
and in terms of the way the model is constructed, how do you deal

998
00:55:48.856 --> 00:55:52.556
with both those missing values, and how does the

999
00:55:52.656 --> 00:55:55.876
model deal with the time factor of

1000
00:55:56.016 --> 00:55:59.976
weighing, say, nearer measurements more heavily on the

1001
00:56:00.036 --> 00:56:03.506
outcome for, say, a risk factor profile than

1002
00:56:03.676 --> 00:56:04.816
measurements from a year ago?

1003
00:56:05.916 --> 00:56:06.196
So,

1004
00:56:07.196 --> 00:56:10.656
two excellent questions. How do we deal with missing data?

1005
00:56:11.356 --> 00:56:15.296
There is not much, really. We can try to interpolate it.

1006
00:56:15.876 --> 00:56:18.286
We usually try to avoid that because

1007
00:56:19.496 --> 00:56:22.996
we're basically guessing that everything remains the same, while it may

1008
00:56:23.016 --> 00:56:23.535
not.

1009
00:56:24.496 --> 00:56:27.306
And we're potentially being convinced

1010
00:56:28.536 --> 00:56:30.916
of certain things that are not really true.

1011
00:56:31.096 --> 00:56:34.496
So usually we deal it like proper missing data,

1012
00:56:35.056 --> 00:56:38.796
and we just say, "Well, we cannot really get to any conclusion

1013
00:56:38.936 --> 00:56:42.576
for this amount of days in which the individual is not wearing it properly."

1014
00:56:43.636 --> 00:56:47.046
As part of some of this study, we also think about incentives

1015
00:56:47.156 --> 00:56:51.096
to help the individual potentially wear the device more and

1016
00:56:51.176 --> 00:56:54.315
eventually remind the individuals to wear the device.

1017
00:56:54.945 --> 00:56:58.116
They may work or may not work depending really on case by case.

1018
00:56:58.256 --> 00:57:00.716
So that's quite complicated.

1019
00:57:01.896 --> 00:57:04.376
Regarding the second question, can you repeat it again?

1020
00:57:04.776 --> 00:57:07.516
Oh, sure. So I was wondering if your model incorporated

1021
00:57:08.396 --> 00:57:10.626
the time decay factor, essentially.

1022
00:57:10.636 --> 00:57:10.876
Sure.

1023
00:57:11.016 --> 00:57:11.716
So, yeah.

1024
00:57:12.236 --> 00:57:14.436
That is true in any of the

1025
00:57:18.136 --> 00:57:21.156
studies that we have done. For infectious diseases, for example,

1026
00:57:23.536 --> 00:57:27.336
first of all, we consider changes with respect to the recent

1027
00:57:27.436 --> 00:57:31.416
past. So we take a window of approximately two months

1028
00:57:31.556 --> 00:57:32.076
before

1029
00:57:33.616 --> 00:57:37.016
the eventual event, in this case, an infectious disease,

1030
00:57:37.596 --> 00:57:41.486
and see if in the last couple of days, there is a significant difference with

1031
00:57:41.556 --> 00:57:42.986
respect to the previous two months.

1032
00:57:44.036 --> 00:57:47.436
We try to forget data that is too far in the past.

1033
00:57:48.116 --> 00:57:51.836
Again, this was for that specific

1034
00:57:51.876 --> 00:57:52.956
analysis. For any

1035
00:57:54.416 --> 00:57:58.156
single cases, any context, we have slightly different choices.

1036
00:57:58.236 --> 00:58:00.416
But this is a really important point.

1037
00:58:00.816 --> 00:58:02.656
We don't consider all the data the same.

1038
00:58:02.676 --> 00:58:04.446
We consider the time, and we try to

1039
00:58:06.116 --> 00:58:07.876
decide what

1040
00:58:08.996 --> 00:58:12.256
technique to use based on the specific context.

1041
00:58:12.896 --> 00:58:13.336
Thank you.

1042
00:58:13.556 --> 00:58:13.896
Thank you.

1043
00:58:14.896 --> 00:58:15.416
Thank you, Giorgio.

1044
00:58:15.756 --> 00:58:16.855
Thank you so much. Thank you.

1045
00:58:20.556 --> 00:58:24.296
And now to our final speaker, George Niava from USC, who's going to bring it back

1046
00:58:24.336 --> 00:58:28.296
to oncologic practice and how wearable sensors and sensor data in

1047
00:58:28.336 --> 00:58:32.226
general together with algorithms might actually influence clinical practice,

1048
00:58:33.236 --> 00:58:36.646
including what barriers are ahead of us to overcome. George, all yours.

1049
00:58:37.976 --> 00:58:41.856
Thank you, Peter. So the fundamental thing that you

1050
00:58:41.876 --> 00:58:45.596
get from sensor data is you're getting data from patients.

1051
00:58:45.676 --> 00:58:49.496
And so I'm going to talk to you about the limitations of that

1052
00:58:49.536 --> 00:58:53.316
data that comes from patients, trying to understand where AI

1053
00:58:53.325 --> 00:58:57.296
integration should be done. We'll give you some examples, and

1054
00:58:57.336 --> 00:59:00.016
then we'll suggest what's going to happen in the future.

1055
00:59:01.336 --> 00:59:04.876
So the first thing is that AI is very good at time

1056
00:59:04.976 --> 00:59:08.456
series data, and I think you've seen some very nice examples of time series data

1057
00:59:08.556 --> 00:59:10.156
from Giorgio and Christina.

1058
00:59:11.216 --> 00:59:15.006
Glucose monitoring, ambulatory blood pressure monitoring, cardiac rhythm

1059
00:59:15.096 --> 00:59:15.685
monitoring,

1060
00:59:16.496 --> 00:59:20.396
and vital sign monitoring of hospitalized patients are all

1061
00:59:20.476 --> 00:59:24.256
areas where it's been clinically shown that having time

1062
00:59:24.336 --> 00:59:27.676
series data is superior to episodic data.

1063
00:59:28.956 --> 00:59:32.756
It leads to early detection of decompensation, better care,

1064
00:59:33.316 --> 00:59:37.006
personalized care. And so the question really that we're

1065
00:59:37.076 --> 00:59:41.006
asking when we're looking at wearables is, are these tools

1066
00:59:41.296 --> 00:59:45.176
which have been very nicely applied in very specific situations,

1067
00:59:45.716 --> 00:59:49.446
should they be applied more broadly to fitness and

1068
00:59:49.496 --> 00:59:49.946
activity?

1069
00:59:51.036 --> 00:59:54.346
And I think everybody got really excited about

1070
00:59:54.376 --> 00:59:56.636
continuous patient-reported data

1071
00:59:57.596 --> 01:00:01.536
after this 2016 presentation, which was a plenary at the

1072
01:00:01.636 --> 01:00:05.436
ASCO meeting from Ethan Basch, which showed that if

1073
01:00:05.496 --> 01:00:08.896
patients simply told a computer

1074
01:00:09.536 --> 01:00:12.076
how they were feeling and what was going on with their life,

1075
01:00:12.876 --> 01:00:16.636
they actually had better survival than if they were monitored by routine

1076
01:00:16.676 --> 01:00:17.386
CT scanning.

1077
01:00:18.636 --> 01:00:20.136
And this was for lung cancer patients.

1078
01:00:21.516 --> 01:00:24.936
So this was very exciting. It showed that they had improvement along

1079
01:00:25.036 --> 01:00:27.376
all series of

1080
01:00:28.976 --> 01:00:32.626
metrics. And you would've thought after this presentation was

1081
01:00:32.656 --> 01:00:36.446
made that we would be doing remote patient

1082
01:00:36.576 --> 01:00:39.516
monitoring for everybody with lung cancer, or maybe all cancers,

1083
01:00:40.776 --> 01:00:41.876
because it improved survival.

1084
01:00:42.956 --> 01:00:45.396
But it didn't happen. And it didn't happen

1085
01:00:45.436 --> 01:00:49.388
becauseA lot of patients aren't health literate,

1086
01:00:49.588 --> 01:00:51.388
can't really do digital health things.

1087
01:00:51.768 --> 01:00:53.608
A lot of patients don't want to do weekly check-ins.

1088
01:00:55.088 --> 01:00:58.288
Clinicians get alert fatigue and really oftentimes don't want to

1089
01:00:58.328 --> 01:00:59.758
hear what's

1090
01:01:00.748 --> 01:01:02.908
happening to every one of their patients.

1091
01:01:02.988 --> 01:01:05.368
Here are places where AI can really be

1092
01:01:06.448 --> 01:01:10.008
a solution. A lot of physicians, I'm not going to say older

1093
01:01:10.048 --> 01:01:13.408
physicians, but there's a lot of skepticism in some demographics.

1094
01:01:15.088 --> 01:01:18.368
And then the question of staffing, who's really watching all of this, and who's

1095
01:01:18.428 --> 01:01:21.978
paying for it? The health systems are really interested

1096
01:01:22.028 --> 01:01:25.988
in revenue. They're really not that interested in increasing

1097
01:01:26.028 --> 01:01:26.628
expenses.

1098
01:01:28.248 --> 01:01:31.788
The IT departments at hospitals are incredibly backed up,

1099
01:01:32.448 --> 01:01:36.248
they're expensive to work with, and they don't like to do pilot

1100
01:01:36.328 --> 01:01:39.048
projects that aren't directly linked to revenue.

1101
01:01:41.208 --> 01:01:41.528
And

1102
01:01:42.628 --> 01:01:45.828
so when you look at the six and a half million cancer

1103
01:01:45.928 --> 01:01:46.668
patients

1104
01:01:47.608 --> 01:01:51.428
that were looked at in the Medicare database, and you ask them, how often was the

1105
01:01:51.467 --> 01:01:55.258
remote patient monitoring code billed for one of those patients,

1106
01:01:55.788 --> 01:01:57.508
it was less than 1% of the time.

1107
01:02:00.048 --> 01:02:03.478
And then the big downer was that when

1108
01:02:03.528 --> 01:02:07.288
the BOCH study was repeated in the PROTECT trial, the

1109
01:02:07.308 --> 01:02:10.878
survival benefit wasn't seen in follow-up in 2025,

1110
01:02:11.448 --> 01:02:14.888
although it was able to detect fewer emergency room

1111
01:02:14.908 --> 01:02:18.568
visits and better preservation of physical functioning for those

1112
01:02:18.608 --> 01:02:22.128
patients who were put on remote patient

1113
01:02:22.188 --> 01:02:22.708
monitoring.

1114
01:02:24.868 --> 01:02:28.588
Now, it's not to say that health systems are totally against remote patient

1115
01:02:28.668 --> 01:02:31.408
monitoring and patient-generated health data.

1116
01:02:31.598 --> 01:02:35.368
There's a bunch of patient-generated health data that they really, really

1117
01:02:35.488 --> 01:02:35.688
like.

1118
01:02:36.938 --> 01:02:39.428
They like psychosocial distress monitoring.

1119
01:02:39.888 --> 01:02:43.748
They love patients entering their own history into history forms.

1120
01:02:45.008 --> 01:02:47.788
They like to get information about quality of life.

1121
01:02:47.828 --> 01:02:50.188
They like patient-reported outcome metrics.

1122
01:02:52.128 --> 01:02:54.668
These things are relatively easy to collect.

1123
01:02:55.197 --> 01:02:58.988
These are things that are all linked to some metric of quality care that's been

1124
01:02:59.028 --> 01:03:01.697
imposed on the hospital system by

1125
01:03:02.928 --> 01:03:04.948
one of the various regulators that they deal with.

1126
01:03:07.088 --> 01:03:09.468
And remote patient monitoring, though, does work.

1127
01:03:10.628 --> 01:03:14.228
This is an example of some obesity trials where they showed that if the

1128
01:03:14.268 --> 01:03:18.188
patients are entered into a remote patient monitoring program, they

1129
01:03:18.288 --> 01:03:21.488
lose more weight than if they get routine care just in the office.

1130
01:03:22.828 --> 01:03:26.188
Now, I'll have you pay attention to the degree of benefit here.

1131
01:03:26.728 --> 01:03:28.508
You see that it's a couple of pounds.

1132
01:03:30.488 --> 01:03:31.648
And this is what AI can do.

1133
01:03:32.628 --> 01:03:34.528
This is data from the Noom app,

1134
01:03:35.328 --> 01:03:36.508
for those who've used Noom.

1135
01:03:37.588 --> 01:03:41.408
And this is in breast cancer patients showing just

1136
01:03:41.488 --> 01:03:45.218
how much difference there is in weight loss, looking

1137
01:03:45.308 --> 01:03:48.568
here at differences of 5% of body weight,

1138
01:03:49.328 --> 01:03:53.137
which can be achieved if you tailor a customized

1139
01:03:53.208 --> 01:03:56.888
artificial intelligence to coach people on weight loss.

1140
01:04:00.048 --> 01:04:03.768
But any time you think about putting people into some kind of

1141
01:04:03.848 --> 01:04:04.688
application,

1142
01:04:06.448 --> 01:04:10.068
not everybody's as good as Dr. Lo is at getting

1143
01:04:10.208 --> 01:04:11.348
long-term adherence.

1144
01:04:12.548 --> 01:04:15.148
And you'll see that for many studies,

1145
01:04:16.308 --> 01:04:19.088
the step count goes down and the

1146
01:04:19.828 --> 01:04:23.148
compliance goes down with time of enrollment.

1147
01:04:25.088 --> 01:04:26.928
And this is even true with wearables,

1148
01:04:27.948 --> 01:04:29.818
which you'd think would be relatively easy.

1149
01:04:30.538 --> 01:04:33.588
We do see a lot better adherence early on in the study.

1150
01:04:33.648 --> 01:04:36.648
We generally see less adherence later.

1151
01:04:38.988 --> 01:04:41.208
And this is some data from our group,

1152
01:04:42.408 --> 01:04:45.748
where we took some patients who had lung cancer,

1153
01:04:46.308 --> 01:04:50.248
who we decided we're going to treat them with a PD-1

1154
01:04:50.308 --> 01:04:52.068
checkpoint inhibitor at home

1155
01:04:53.048 --> 01:04:56.628
with subcutaneous administration, and we're going to have all the visits be by

1156
01:04:56.688 --> 01:04:59.508
telemedicine. We're not going to make them come into the office.

1157
01:04:59.528 --> 01:05:03.468
We're going to give them their drug at home, and we're going to see

1158
01:05:03.488 --> 01:05:06.348
them just by telemedicine and monitor them with wearables.

1159
01:05:06.868 --> 01:05:10.008
And we ask them to upload their vital signs just before their doctor's visits.

1160
01:05:10.968 --> 01:05:14.148
And what you can see is that compliance is very different

1161
01:05:14.608 --> 01:05:18.258
depending on which specific task you're asking them to do.

1162
01:05:19.028 --> 01:05:22.248
Vital sign compliance was really good because they knew they were about to see me,

1163
01:05:22.288 --> 01:05:25.128
and they'd get yelled at if they didn't upload their vital signs, right?

1164
01:05:25.968 --> 01:05:29.888
But wearing the Fitbit was not as good for a lot of people.

1165
01:05:29.928 --> 01:05:31.048
Some people had trouble

1166
01:05:31.848 --> 01:05:35.108
remembering to charge the device. We didn't have the one-week charging.

1167
01:05:35.948 --> 01:05:37.888
We were more on the three-day charging plan.

1168
01:05:38.508 --> 01:05:38.748
And

1169
01:05:39.708 --> 01:05:42.508
then completing surveys, quality of life surveys.

1170
01:05:43.868 --> 01:05:45.568
People just sometimes just don't get around to it.

1171
01:05:48.248 --> 01:05:51.138
When you think about cancer patients and activity,

1172
01:05:52.968 --> 01:05:56.888
I think Georgia did a very nice job of talking about how variable it is

1173
01:05:57.068 --> 01:05:58.728
among different patient populations.

1174
01:05:59.428 --> 01:06:02.958
And this is a nice meta-analysis done by Gillian Gresham,

1175
01:06:03.748 --> 01:06:07.028
show that cancer patients are not super active in

1176
01:06:07.068 --> 01:06:08.048
general.

1177
01:06:09.168 --> 01:06:13.008
Some of these people are walking 3,000, 4,000 steps a day.

1178
01:06:13.028 --> 01:06:15.988
Some studies have higher numbers.

1179
01:06:16.008 --> 01:06:19.068
But the important thing to keep in mind is that it's not

1180
01:06:19.668 --> 01:06:23.588
patients getting to the point where they're not running marathons and they're not

1181
01:06:23.628 --> 01:06:27.378
going out jogging. The real question for many of these cancer patients is,

1182
01:06:27.668 --> 01:06:29.088
did they vacuum their carpet or not?

1183
01:06:32.708 --> 01:06:36.438
And physical functioning is one place that is

1184
01:06:36.668 --> 01:06:40.558
ripe for AI tools to help us solve the

1185
01:06:40.628 --> 01:06:41.148
problem.

1186
01:06:42.248 --> 01:06:45.868
This is an old study done out of the Mayo Clinic

1187
01:06:45.888 --> 01:06:46.528
Consortium,

1188
01:06:47.328 --> 01:06:49.728
which looked at measurement of performance status.

1189
01:06:50.148 --> 01:06:53.928
Now, for those of you who measure performance status using the ECOG

1190
01:06:54.008 --> 01:06:57.678
scale, you know there's only five choices.The

1191
01:06:57.688 --> 01:06:59.478
patients are up and active,

1192
01:07:00.318 --> 01:07:03.998
they can be bedridden, and then they can have various degrees of bedridden in

1193
01:07:04.018 --> 01:07:07.038
between. So if you were to ask

1194
01:07:08.558 --> 01:07:12.448
a roll of the dice how often you would be accurate to hit

1195
01:07:12.478 --> 01:07:12.878
the same

1196
01:07:14.578 --> 01:07:15.888
performance status measurement,

1197
01:07:17.978 --> 01:07:21.518
with the physician being asked what the performance status is and the patient being

1198
01:07:21.598 --> 01:07:23.628
asked what they think their performance status is.

1199
01:07:24.158 --> 01:07:26.318
If it was random, you'd be right 20% of the time.

1200
01:07:26.658 --> 01:07:28.858
If you're a physician, you're only right 40% of the time.

1201
01:07:31.018 --> 01:07:34.318
And this is something where you'd think it'd be

1202
01:07:34.478 --> 01:07:37.698
relatively simple, and it's not.

1203
01:07:38.487 --> 01:07:42.418
And the problem is that when there's disagreement between the patient

1204
01:07:42.738 --> 01:07:46.578
and the physician in terms of what the patient's performance status

1205
01:07:46.698 --> 01:07:46.978
is,

1206
01:07:47.878 --> 01:07:51.158
there is an increased risk of death for the patient.

1207
01:07:52.038 --> 01:07:54.858
It leads to over-treatment, and it leads to under-treatment.

1208
01:07:55.288 --> 01:07:59.018
Most of the time, the physicians are overestimating performance

1209
01:07:59.078 --> 01:07:59.518
status.

1210
01:08:01.737 --> 01:08:05.478
And to give you a sense of how much of a difference it is, it's about a

1211
01:08:05.498 --> 01:08:09.178
16% difference in survival, which is approximately the

1212
01:08:09.258 --> 01:08:13.138
same benefit that you get from giving cisplatin chemotherapy

1213
01:08:13.658 --> 01:08:15.718
in the adjuvant setting to a lung cancer patient.

1214
01:08:18.659 --> 01:08:19.579
So we asked

1215
01:08:21.358 --> 01:08:22.818
an AI tool,

1216
01:08:25.239 --> 01:08:26.098
Xbox Kinect,

1217
01:08:27.038 --> 01:08:30.678
to look at people as they move

1218
01:08:30.758 --> 01:08:33.418
from the chair in the examination room,

1219
01:08:34.538 --> 01:08:36.938
getting onto the table in the examination room.

1220
01:08:37.958 --> 01:08:39.848
And we measured velocity,

1221
01:08:40.678 --> 01:08:44.298
acceleration of that movement, and we were able to

1222
01:08:44.378 --> 01:08:48.358
calculate a performance status score from that camera

1223
01:08:48.918 --> 01:08:50.098
of how the patient is doing.

1224
01:08:51.458 --> 01:08:54.138
Now, to give you a sense of

1225
01:08:55.418 --> 01:08:56.418
how nice that is,

1226
01:08:57.598 --> 01:09:01.018
the heat map that you see on the left is

1227
01:09:01.098 --> 01:09:04.199
how 35 different patients

1228
01:09:05.018 --> 01:09:07.298
were scored looking at the video of the

1229
01:09:09.119 --> 01:09:12.978
same movement, and what performance status score the patient was given on the

1230
01:09:12.998 --> 01:09:13.938
Karnofsky Scale.

1231
01:09:15.098 --> 01:09:19.038
And you can see here, physician number three is extremely pessimistic.

1232
01:09:19.338 --> 01:09:22.558
Physician number one and four are much more optimistic.

1233
01:09:22.598 --> 01:09:24.718
Physician number two is in the middle.

1234
01:09:24.918 --> 01:09:28.619
But what you can see here is that there's a tremendous amount of variability in how

1235
01:09:28.659 --> 01:09:30.779
the human eye scores activity.

1236
01:09:32.079 --> 01:09:35.878
And here's a place where AI can help, and this is work done by

1237
01:09:35.958 --> 01:09:37.079
Chris Wang in our group.

1238
01:09:39.659 --> 01:09:40.739
And we know that,

1239
01:09:41.798 --> 01:09:44.138
